📌 Overview

This project analyzes the HR Employee Attrition dataset to uncover patterns behind employee turnover — age, department, tenure, salary band, education, and gender — and translates those patterns into actionable HR recommendations. The report is built as a 3-page narrative: Dashboard → Insights → Recommendations.

📄 Report Pages

1. Dashboard

Interactive overview with slicers (Age, Department, Gender) and KPI cards for Employee Count, Attrition, Average Age, Average Monthly Income, and Average Years at Company, plus:


Attrition count by department (combo chart)
Attrition trend by years at company (area chart)
Job Role × Job Satisfaction pivot table
Attrition by education field (funnel)
Attrition vs. salary hike (bar chart)
Attrition by job level (area chart)


2. Insights

Key findings extracted from the data:


Average age of employees who left: 37 years
Research & Development had the highest attrition — 133 departures (56% attrition rate), vs. Sales (39%) and HR (5%)
69% of employees who left earned below $5,000/month
Highest attrition by tenure: 1 year (25%), then 2 years (11%) and 5 years (9%)
Educational background of leavers: Life Science (89), Medical (63), Marketing (35)
Attrition rate by gender: Male 17% vs. Female 14.8%


3. Recommendations

Data-driven actions for HR, including:


Targeted retention strategies for employees around 40 years old
Focused intervention on Research & Development attrition
Improved compensation for lower salary bands
Early-career engagement initiatives
Career growth paths aligned to educational background
Diversity & inclusion focus on gender attrition gaps
Regular salary benchmarking to stay competitive


🧰 Tools & Skills


Power BI Desktop — data modeling, report design, storytelling layout
DAX — custom measures (Attrition Count, Average Age, Average Monthly Income, Average Years at Company)
Interactive slicers, combo/area/funnel/bar charts, pivot tables, action buttons for page navigation
